'''Martin Copley''' (1940 – 30 July 2014) was a British-born [[Australia]]n [[conservation biology|conservationist]] and [[philanthropy|philanthropist]] who established the [[Australian Wildlife Conservancy]] (AWC), an organisation which purchases and manages large areas of land, mainly former [[pastoral lease|pastoral properties]], as [[nature reserve]]s (called 'sanctuaries') for the conservation of [[biodiversity]].<ref name=GNT38>[http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/people/Transcripts/s1087017.htm ABC program archive: George Negus Tonight 38, broadcast 13 April 2004] accessed 8 January 2008</ref>

Copley was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[financier]] and insurance [[underwriter]].  He first visited Australia in 1966.  In 1991 he purchased a property containing a large area of natural bushland at [[Chidlow, Western Australia]], now the [[Karakamia Sanctuary]], for conservation purposes, effectively founding what was to become the AWC.<ref name=NTAWA>[http://www.ntwa.com.au/convention/paperBWilson.shtml National Trust of Australia (WA): paper by Barry Wilson to the State Heritage Convention]</ref>  In 1994 he moved to Australia permanently.<ref name=GNT38/>  In 2001 the AWC became a public charitable organisation.<ref name=AWC>[http://www.australianwildlife.org/aboutAWC.asp Australian Wildlife Conservancy: About AWC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226071644/http://www.australianwildlife.org/aboutawc.asp |date=2007-12-26 }}</ref> Copley died of cancer on 30 July 2014. <ref name=AWC2>[http://www.australianwildlife.org/about/directors.aspx Australian Wildlife Conservancy: Board of Directors]</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/martin-copley-saviour-of-native-animals-dies-aged-74/story-e6frg6nf-1227009285623?nk=26716b73f26605e3974ceecae0bb8d8b|publisher=The Australian|title=Martin Copley, saviour of native animals, dies aged 74|date=1 August 2014|author=Paige Taylor}}</ref>

