{{Infobox storm |name = March 2018 Western European Blizzard
|alt = |stormtype = Winter storm |date formed = 26 February 2018 |date dissipated = 5 March 2018 |maximum amount = {{convert|57|cm|in}} [[Little Rissington]] <ref name="trevorharley.com">{{cite web|url=http://trevorharley.com/weather_web_pages/british_weather_in_march.htm|title=British_weather_in_March.htm|website=trevorharley.com}}</ref> |pressure = |lowest temperature = |sustained wind = |gust = |total damages (USD) = |total fatalities = 16 <ref name="report-from-the-sun">{{cite web|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/5714337/storm-emma-rain-floods-uk-weather-warning-devon-evacuate/|title=Families told 'evacuate now' as storm brings intense flooding|date=3 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref> |areas affected = Western Europe }}
{{See also|2018 Great Britain and Ireland cold wave|2017–18 European windstorm season}} '''Storm Emma''', also called Ulrike, was an event that was part of the 2018 Great Britain and Ireland cold wave and the 2017–18 European Windstorm Season. The Low Pressure System interacted with Cold air that had been firmly established over Western Europe for a few days, leading to heavy snow falls of up to {{convert|57|cm|in}}<ref name="trevorharley.com"/>. It also brought a renewed push of cold air to much of the United Kingdom with temperatures falling as low as {{convert|-11|C|F}} in Nairnshire <ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/26/uk-braces-for-beast-from-the-east-as-met-office-warns-of-snow|title=UK braces for extreme weather as Met Office warns of snow|first=Patrick|last=Greenfield|date=26 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="trevorharley.com"/>. The worst affected areas were South west England and Southern Wales<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43236763|title=Storm Emma to bring up to 50cm of snow|date=2018-03-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> where an estimated 16 people died in connection with the storm<ref name="report-from-the-sun" />.
==Snowfall, and temperatures== ===Snowfall=== Although the maximum snow fall was {{convert|57|cm|in}}, most places affected reported a general total of {{convert|50|cm|in}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-weather-today-friday-storm-emma-snow-road-conditions-trains-power-cut-gas-a8235776.html|title=Storm Emma to blanket UK in 50cm of snow, causing more misery for travellers|date=1 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Snowfall was reported along the coast of Italy and [[French Riviera]] for the first time since 2010<ref>https://www.thelocal.fr/20180226/in-pictures-french-riviera-in-the-snow</ref>. Snow also fell in [[Barcelona]], a rare occurrence for the region.<ref>https://www.barcelonayellow.com/bcn-photos/363-snow-in-barcelona-march-2010</ref>
===Temperatures=== Throughout the period of the storm, the temperatures were very suppressed with [[Tredegar]] recording a daytime high of {{convert|-5|C|F}} however more generally there was a maximum of {{convert|-2|C|F}}.<ref name="trevorharley.com"/>
